source.422a94e5: # Introduction * In this kernel, we will analyze and predict house prices. While analyzing and cleaning data for prediction we will use **Data Science Helper**(DSH) library. This library is written by me and created for saving time and making data science operations with less effort. * Github Link for DSH: https://github.com/bayhippo/Data-Science-Helper * You can check out another kernel about this library and data analysis: https://www.kaggle.com/mrhippo/house-price-prediction-and-analysis-with-dsh
source.5cab9a75:
* When we look at the info some of the features are containing NaN(Not a Number) values. We have to fill these values for analysis and ML modeling.
* **How to fill a numeric feature:** We can use: **Mean**, **Median** and **Mode** but we will just use mean.
* **How to fill a categorical feature:** There are not that many options, we will fill them with the most frequent feature.
* We will use **Data Science Helper**'s functions to do that.
source.0ef08159: * In categorical features some of the values can be dominant than others. So we can distinguish data as binary according to these features. We will use **"categorical_features_as_binary"** function of **Data Science Helper**. This function labels **the most frequent value as 1**, **other values as 0**.

source.a4e12387:
* When we look at the data we can see that some of the features are not that meaningful and some of them are useless.
* **Cabin:** The cabin number of the passenger. We cannot analyze this feature.
* **Name:** Can be useful with feature engineering but we will pass it, if you want to see how to apply feature engineering to this feature you can check out this kernel: https://www.kaggle.com/kanncaa1/dataiteam-titanic-eda
* **PassengerId:** Not useful and can be a problem with ML models.
* **Ticket:** Not useful and cannot be analyzed.
* So we will drop these columns.
source.ab0514d1: * Sometimes our data might contain features that looking like numerical but categorical in real. For example: Room number of a house seems like numeric but it is a categorical feature. * We can find out that using **"find_numericlike_categorical_features"** function of **Data Science Helper**. This function takes data's features and a filter feature, filter feature should be a feature that has a high variance and standard deviation.
source.1427a4a5: * In numerical features we can label some of the gaps. We are assuming that we have a **normal distribution**. There are **3 standard deviation levels**. * We will use **"numeric_features_as_5_classes"** function of **Data Science Helper**. This function labels values according to mean and standard deviation.
